1 "§ 30-51. Principles of law and equity.
2 The principles of law and equity supplement this Article except to the extent inconsistent
3 with this Article.
4 "§ 30-52. Uniformity of application and construction.
5 In applying and construing this Article, a court shall consider the promotion of uniformity of
6 the law among jurisdictions that enact the Uniform Community Property Disposition at Death
7 Act."
8 SECTION 3. G.S. 28A-2-4 reads as rewritten:
9 "§ 28A-2-4. Subject matter jurisdiction of the clerk of superior court in estate proceedings.
10 (a) The clerks of superior court of this State, as ex officio judges of probate, shall have
11 original jurisdiction of estate proceedings. Except as provided in subdivision (4) of this
12 subsection, the jurisdiction of the clerk of superior court is exclusive. Estate proceedings include,
13 but are not limited to, the following:
14 …
15 (4) Proceedings to ascertain heirs or devisees, to approve settlement agreements
16 pursuant to G.S. 28A-2-10, to determine questions of construction of wills, to
17 determine priority among creditors, to determine whether a person is in
18 possession of property belonging to an estate, to order the recovery of property
19 of the estate in possession of third parties, to determine a claim for relief
20 regarding the disposition of community property at death as provided in
21 Article 5 of Chapter 30 of the General Statutes, and to determine the existence
22 or nonexistence of any immunity, power, privilege, duty, or right. Any party
23 or the clerk of superior court may file a notice of transfer of a proceeding
24 pursuant to this subdivision to the Superior Court Division of the General
25 Court of Justice as provided in G.S. 28A-2-6(h). In the absence of a transfer
26 to superior court, Article 26 of Chapter 1 of the General Statutes shall apply
27 applies to an estate proceeding pending before the clerk of superior court to
28 the extent consistent with this Article.
29 (b) Nothing in this section shall affect affects the right of a person to file an action in the
30 Superior Court Division of the General Court of Justice for declaratory relief under Article 26 of
31 Chapter 1 of the General Statutes. In the event that either the petitioner or the respondent in an
32 estate proceeding requests declaratory relief under Article 26 of Chapter 1 of the General
33 Statutes, either party may move for a transfer of the proceeding to the Superior Court Division
34 of the General Court of Justice as provided in Article 21 of Chapter 7A of the General Statutes.
35 In the absence of a removal to superior court, Article 26 of Chapter 1 of the General Statutes
36 shall apply applies to an estate proceeding to the extent consistent with this Article.
37 (c) Without otherwise limiting the jurisdiction of the Superior Court Division of the
38 General Court of Justice, the clerk of superior court shall does not have jurisdiction under
39 subsection (a) or (b) of this section or G.S. 28A-2-5 of the following:
40 …
41 (4) Proceeding Proceedings to determine proper county of venue as provided in
42 G.S. 28A-3-2.
43 …."
44 SECTION 4. If a provision of this act or its application to a person or circumstance
45 is held invalid, the invalidity does not affect another provision or application that can be given
46 effect without the invalid provision.
47 SECTION 5. The Revisor of Statutes shall cause to be printed, as annotations to the
48 published General Statutes, all relevant portions of the Official Comments to the Uniform
49 Community Property Disposition at Death Act and all explanatory comments of the drafters of
50 this act as the Revisor may deem appropriate.
